    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1921-09-30T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1921-09-30T18:00:00-05:00" n="131"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d131">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">813.00/1105: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in Honduras</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Spencer</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1921-09-30T18:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 30, 1921—6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>37. Your despatch 185, August 16, 1921.<note n="39" xml:id="d131fn39">Not
                        printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Cable Department whether so-called interpretation of Monroe Doctrine, as
                    communicated to the Government of Salvador in February, 1920, by the Department
                    of State,<note n="40" xml:id="d131fn40">See note of Feb. 26, 1920, to the
                        Salvadoran Minister, <ref target="frus1920v02#pg_226">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1920, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p. 226</ref>.</note> has been inserted in
                    Central American Constitution.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hughes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
